				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I think other waves could be not so hard to do. A square wave wouldn't require any DAC, just a transistor to buffer a TTL output (because it would be bad to directly connect the TTL output to the sound pin). Note that my shematic won't work, you need 2 more 4-bits D flip-flops on the inputs of the freqency counters, plus some logic that re-triggers those counters when the sawtooth counter overflows. You could just XOR the low 3 bits with the higher bit to get a 8-step triangle wave, and it would require an additional chip, but less resistors for a 3-bit DAC. It would sound similar but a lot more distorted than the NES' triangle wave.
<br />
<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Bregalad: Is there a reason that you started out with a divide by 10 counter instead of a divide by 16? Wouldn't a divide by 16 let the program use the same note period tables as with the built-in channels?</div>
<br />Maybe so. I haven't checked exactly. If that's the case, definitely a divider by 16 would be better.
<br />
<br />EDIT : It would also be interesting to create analog-based sound generators. This shouldn't be too complicated, but to get precision in frequency it is. Typically, with an operationnal amplifier with a capacity between the inverted input and the output, you can charge it lineary and get a linear voltage on the ouput. I think you could detect when the voltage approach the power voltage and revert the voltage on the input of the operationnal amplifier to discharge the capacity lineary. A JFET transistor could simulate a variable resistor on the input of the operational amplifier to get a variable frequency. The oupout would be a non-distorted triangle wave. It also require few componant. However, a 8-bit DAC would be needed to control the JFET transisor, and I think the frequency would be atrociously detuned in the best case, due to the imprecision of the transistor and of the capacity.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Life is complex: it has both real and imaginary components.</div>
